<table>

<tr>
<td width="44%">
<h2><b>Security in IPv6</b></h2>

This course looks at the security
implications arising from the <em>differences</em> between IPv4 and IPv6. The scope
is strictly IPv6, but also requires a good understanding of
IPv4. We will provide references, practical exercises,
demonstrations, and mitigation techniques.
This a one-day course. 

<br /> <br />
Familiarity with the basics of IPv6 is required, 
but the following topics will be briefly revised:    
<br />
<ul> 
   <li> IPv6 address types - multicast, GUA, link local
   <li> address lifetimes - tentative, preferred, deprecated, invalid
   <li> Layer 3 multicast, Layer 2 multicast
   <li> extension headers and fragmentation
   <li> Neighbour Discovery, Router Advertisement
   <li> Stateless address autoconfiguration, DHCPv6
</ul> 
</td>

<td width="28%">
<h2>Outline</h2>
<ul>
<li> How IPv6 differs from IPv4 </li>
<li> Security implications of those differences </li>
<li> Newness as a security issue </li>
<li> IPSec protocol suite </li>
<li> The IPv6 header </li>
<li> IPv6 extension headers - misused, unnecessary, broken </li>
<li> IPv6 extension header option fields - bad length, unknown, probe tools, attack vector </li>
<li> IPv6 fragmentation - hiding payloads, unnecessary, overlapping, disjoint, broken, exhausting target, ID prediction </li>
<li> ICMPv6, Path MTU Discovery </li>
</ul>
</td>

<td width="28%">
<h2>&nbsp;</h2>
<ul>
<li> Neighbor Discovery: protection, Secure Neighbor Discovery </li>
<li> ND spoofing in general - redirecting traffic, blackholing, Denial of Service </li>
<li> ND cache exhaustion - remote DoD, stateless ND </li>
<li> Router Advertisement spoofing - prefix flooding, prefix hijacking,
prefix wrapping, DHCPv6 flags </li>
<li> Simplicity as a security positive </li>
<li> IPv6 and scanning attacks </li>
<li> SLAAC and security/privacy </li>
<li> Dual-stack as a security issue </li>
<li> Automatic tunnelling </li>

</ul>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h2>Conditions</h2>

Courses are held on-site or at specialised capital city premises. They can be
tailored to specific requirements, or arranged for different dates or
locations.  Discounts for multiple attendees are available.  Bookings are
essential, courses must be paid for in advance, and we reserve the right
to cancel any course.  

<a href="terms.php">See the full Training Terms &amp; Conditions.</a>
